PART C — SEMINAR QUESTION ANSWER GRIDS
Structured answers to each seminar question. For exam use: adapt into ILAW/ILAC format with citations in OSCOLA.

Q1a: What is the purpose of judicial review? How does it relate to constitutional principles?
Core Purpose	Judicial review is the mechanism by which the High Court (and appellate courts) supervise the exercise of public power. Its purpose is to ensure that public bodies act within the law — not to determine whether a decision was correct on its merits, but whether the decision-maker acted lawfully. The constitutional foundations are the rule of law and parliamentary sovereignty.
Constitutional Link	Judicial review enforces limits on executive power set by Parliament (ultra vires principle) and by common law (legality, rationality, procedural fairness — CCSU v Minister for Civil Service [1985] AC 374). It gives effect to the principle that no body — including government — is above the law. McAleenon [2024] UKSC 31 [40]–[47] confirms this supervisory function is constitutionally grounded in the rule of law.
vs Appeal	On appeal, the appellate court asks: 'Was the decision right?' It can substitute its own judgment. In judicial review, the court asks: 'Was the decision made lawfully?' It does not substitute its view — it supervises the process and the legal limits on the exercise of power.
Public vs Private	Judicial review addresses public wrongs — unlawful exercises of public power affecting individuals or groups. Private law (tort, contract) addresses private wrongs between individuals. JR is concerned with the relationship between citizen and state, enforcing public law obligations on public bodies.
Cases to cite	CCSU v Minister for Civil Service [1985] AC 374 • In re McAleenon [2024] UKSC 31 • Michalak v GMC [2017] UKSC 71


Q1b: Who is best placed to determine whether a decision is proportionate?
The Tension	This question goes to the heart of the judicial deference debate. Courts possess legal expertise and independence, but lack democratic accountability and specialist policy knowledge. The elected government has democratic legitimacy and access to information courts do not — particularly in areas like national security (U3) and welfare policy (SC).
Judicial View	Lord Reed in SC [2021] argues that polycentric policy decisions involving resource allocation are best left to Parliament and the executive, subject only to a 'manifestly without reasonable foundation' check. Lord Kerr in Keyu [275] argues courts — with their structured proportionality framework — are actually better placed to assess rights impacts than political actors with competing interests.
Academic View	Lock (2021) argues 'democratic accountability' as a basis for deference is circular — Parliament rarely scrutinises individual executive decisions, so deference to the executive on grounds of 'democratic accountability' is fiction. Graham (2025) argues that maximal deference in discrimination/welfare cases guts the protection Article 14 is supposed to provide.
Cases to cite	R (SC) v SSWP [2021] UKSC 26 • R (Keyu) v SSFCA [2015] UKSC 69 • U3 v SSHD [2025] UKSC 19


Q2a: What happened in Tigere? Compare majority and minority approaches to proportionality.
Facts (brief)	Zambian national raised in UK since age 6. Refused student loan because she lacked ILR. Challenge under A2P1 + Article 14 ECHR.
Majority (Lady Hale)	Applied full four-stage structured proportionality (Michalak). Held the blanket ILR exclusion failed stage (iii) — a less restrictive means was available (e.g. requiring 'settled intention to remain'). The rule was disproportionate as applied to someone like Tigere with deep UK ties and no realistic prospect of leaving.
Minority (Sumption/Reed)	Applied 'manifestly without reasonable foundation'. Student loan policy is a resource-allocation decision within Parliament's competence. Courts should not fashion alternative eligibility criteria — that is legislative function. The policy was not irrational or manifestly without justification.
Why the Difference?	Reflects deeper disagreement about the judicial role. Lady Hale accepts courts can identify less restrictive alternatives even in policy areas. Lord Sumption sees this as merits substitution incompatible with parliamentary democracy and the separation of powers. The difference is institutional, not just technical.
What it Shows	Proportionality is not a single fixed test — it is a variable depending on judicial philosophy. The same four stages can be applied with very different intensities. This renders the test unpredictable and, critics argue, insufficiently principled.
Cases to cite	R (Tigere) v SSWP [2015] UKSC 57 • R (SC) v SSWP [2021] UKSC 26 (subsequent development) • Michalak v GMC [2017] UKSC 71


Q2b: What was at issue in SC? Why 'manifestly without reasonable foundation' in a human rights case?
Issue	Two-child benefit limit. Argued to violate Article 14 + A1P1/A2P1 by discriminating on grounds of family size and, indirectly, religion. Core tension: applying MWRF to a case involving human rights seems to weaken rights protection.
Why MWRF?	Lord Reed [113]–[152]: measures of macro-economic/social policy involving redistribution of limited resources attract a wide margin of appreciation. Parliament has democratic accountability for welfare policy choices. Courts lack expertise to assess the complex polycentric trade-offs involved. MWRF acknowledges courts will intervene only where the policy foundation is absent — not merely where they would have chosen differently.
Higher or Lower Bar?	MWRF is a higher bar for claimants than full structured proportionality. Under structured proportionality, the state must justify each stage (rational connection, necessity, fair balance). Under MWRF, the claimant must show there is no reasonable foundation at all for the measure — a near-impossible threshold for complex welfare policy.
Deference	SC shows deference operates on a spectrum. The more a case involves: (1) polycentric policy choices; (2) parliamentary mandate; (3) resource allocation; and (4) an area where Parliament has clear democratic accountability, the more the court defers. But SC also makes clear that evidence and reasoning must still be presented — MWRF is not an automatic shield.
Cases to cite	R (SC, CB) v SSWP [2021] UKSC 26 • R (Tigere) v SSWP [2015] UKSC 57 • R (Keyu) v SSFCA [2015] UKSC 69


Q3a: What is irrationality/unreasonableness in judicial review?
Definition	Irrationality (Wednesbury unreasonableness) is a ground of judicial review whereby a court will quash a decision that is 'so unreasonable that no reasonable authority could ever have come to it': Associated Provincial Picture Houses Ltd v Wednesbury Corporation [1948] 1 KB 223 (Lord Greene MR). The standard is deliberately high — courts should not intervene merely because they disagree with the decision.
When It Applies	Irrationality applies in non-HRA judicial review cases where the challenge is to the substantive content of a decision (rather than its procedure or legality). Examples: decisions based on legally irrelevant factors; decisions that give no weight to relevant considerations; decisions with no logical basis at all.
Sub-species	Courts have recognised sub-species: (1) decisions based on irrelevant considerations; (2) failure to consider relevant matters; (3) bad faith; (4) perversity (the 'outrageous' standard from CCSU). The test has been described as a 'sliding scale' — more intensive where fundamental rights are engaged even in non-HRA cases.
Modern Wednesbury	In cases engaging fundamental rights (even without HRA), courts apply 'anxious scrutiny' — a more intensive form of irrationality review: R v Ministry of Defence, ex p Smith [1996] QB 517 (CA). The closer the decision comes to fundamental rights, the more the court will scrutinise the quality of the reasoning. This blurs the line with proportionality.
Cases to cite	Associated Provincial Picture Houses v Wednesbury Corp [1948] 1 KB 223 • CCSU v Minister for Civil Service [1985] AC 374 • R v MOD ex p Smith [1996] QB 517 • R (Keyu) v SSFCA [2015] UKSC 69


Q3b: Similarities and differences between irrationality and proportionality. Is irrationality always more deferential?
Similarities	Both are substantive grounds of review (they challenge the content of a decision, not merely the process). Both acknowledge that courts should not substitute their own view on merits. Both accept variable intensity of scrutiny depending on context.
Differences	Proportionality: structured four-stage test; places burden on the state to justify; asks if there was a less restrictive means; requires a fair balance of costs and benefits. Irrationality: asks only whether decision was within the range of reasonable outcomes; no structured stages; burden is on claimant to show the decision was beyond that range.
Always More Deferential?	Not necessarily. 'Super-Wednesbury' (anxious scrutiny in rights cases) can approach proportionality in intensity: ex p Smith. Conversely, MWRF (applied in SC) is arguably less intensive than anxious scrutiny in some contexts. The line between an irrationality challenge and a proportionality challenge can collapse in practice. Lord Kerr in Keyu argues Wednesbury is so flexible it has no fixed content.
Key Distinction	The formal distinction: proportionality applies where ECHR rights are engaged (HRA 1998); irrationality applies in non-ECHR cases. This two-track system was criticised in Keyu as unprincipled — Lord Kerr would unify them. Lord Neuberger declined to do so at [131]–[133] as a constitutional question for a nine-justice court.
Cases to cite	R (Keyu) v SSFCA [2015] UKSC 69 • Bank Mellat v HM Treasury (No 2) [2013] UKSC 39 • R v MOD ex p Smith [1996] QB 517 • R (SC) v SSWP [2021] UKSC 26


Q3c: Why did Lord Neuberger decline to replace irrationality with proportionality in Keyu? What does Lord Kerr say?
Lord Neuberger [131]–[133]	It would be a constitutional change of the first order to replace the Wednesbury test with proportionality across all judicial review cases. Such a change is not appropriate to be made by a five-justice panel on a case not specifically raising this question as the central issue. A nine-justice court, properly constituted and with full argument, would be required. Furthermore, even if desirable in principle, replacing irrationality risks making courts into second decision-makers — this threatens the separation of powers.
Lord Kerr [271]–[284]	Proportionality is analytically superior to Wednesbury: it is structured, transparent, and principled. Wednesbury's famous formulation ('so unreasonable that no reasonable authority...') is circular and unpredictable. The rule of law requires that all public decisions meet a standard of justification — why should that standard depend on whether a Convention right happens to be engaged? A unified proportionality test would give certainty and enhance accountability.
Current Position	English law retains the two-track system: proportionality (HRA/EU law cases); irrationality (common law JR). The UKSC has repeatedly declined to unify them — see also Pham v SSHD [2015] UKSC 19. Post-Brexit, the question becomes more pressing as EU law no longer mandates proportionality in domestic courts.
Cases to cite	R (Keyu) v SSFCA [2015] UKSC 69 • Pham v SSHD [2015] UKSC 19 • Associated Provincial Picture Houses v Wednesbury Corp [1948] 1 KB 223


Q4: Case Study: U3 — national security, SIAC, evaluative judgment, constitutional principles
What Was at Issue	Deprivation of British citizenship on national security grounds under s.40(2) British Nationality Act 1981. U3 (Shamima Begum) challenged the decision before SIAC. Core issues: the depth of scrutiny available to courts/SIAC when the executive invokes national security, and what 'evaluative judgment' deference means.
What is SIAC?	The Special Immigration Appeals Commission is a specialist tribunal established by the Special Immigration Appeals Commission Act 1997. It hears immigration and nationality appeals in cases involving classified/closed material (national security intelligence). It can hear 'closed' evidence that is not disclosed to the applicant or their open lawyers. SIAC provides a form of judicial oversight of national security decisions that ordinary courts cannot provide, because it can engage with classified material.
Evaluative Judgment	Lord Reed in U3 uses this term for judgments that require the weighing of incommensurable values by a body with specialist expertise: assessing the credibility of intelligence, the gravity of a threat, the reliability of sources. Courts give significant deference to these judgments because (a) they lack access to the underlying intelligence; (b) the executive has specialist expertise; and (c) national security decisions carry democratic accountability.
Constitutional Principles	1. Separation of powers: national security is an area where the executive has primacy. 2. Democratic accountability: the executive (through Ministers) is accountable to Parliament for security decisions — courts cannot replicate this. 3. Rule of law: even national security decisions must be reviewable, but the scope of review is calibrated. SIAC provides the institutional mechanism for rights-compliant oversight of closed material.
Lock Critique	Lock (2021) argues that 'democratic accountability' as a basis for deference is weak in national security cases: Parliament cannot scrutinise closed intelligence. The accountability is therefore formal (Ministerial responsibility) rather than real (parliamentary scrutiny of the actual decision). This undermines the constitutional justification for deference in U3-type cases.
Cases to cite	U3 v SSHD [2025] UKSC 19 • Begum v SSHD [2021] UKSC 7 • R (Keyu) v SSFCA [2015] UKSC 69 • R (SC) v SSWP [2021] UKSC 26



